Here's what you need — three MAUI APIs on `Application.Current`:

| Goal | API |
|---|---|
| Read system theme | `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` |
| React to changes | `Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged` event |
| Force a theme | `Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark` |

**Example — wire it up in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Log the theme at startup
        Debug.WriteLine($"Current theme: {RequestedTheme}");

        // Subscribe to real-time system theme changes
        RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
            // Update any custom colours / resources here
        };
    }
}
```

**Let the user force a theme (e.g. from a settings page):**

```csharp
// Force dark mode regardless of system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Respond in XAML with `AppThemeBinding`:**

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

`AppThemeBinding` reacts automatically to both system changes **and** `UserAppTheme` overrides — no manual refresh needed.

**Key gotcha:** `RequestedThemeChanged` fires only for *system* changes. Setting `UserAppTheme` does **not** raise the event, so if you need to log user-forced switches too, do it at the call site where you set `UserAppTheme`.
